s a `Functor α Type`.\n\nThere must be an error in the formalization. Let's look at the original problem statement.\n\"1.3.11 / exercise 1.3.iv Define the functor Homc which maps an object c ∈ α to the set Homc(X, Y ) = Hom(X, c) and maps a morphism f : X → Y to the function Hom(X, f) : Homc(Y, Z) → Homc(X, Z) (precomposition with f).\"\nThe formalization `def Hom_c_? {α : Type*} [Category α] (c : α) : Functor α Type where F Y := Hom c Y ...` is incorrect.\nThe codomain of the functor should be `Type`, but the map on objects `F Y := Hom c Y` suggests the codomain is `Type`, but the map on morphisms `homF {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) := g ≫ f` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`, which is not `Type`. This is a type error.\nFurthermore, the `map_comp` goal is an equality between functions of different types (`Hom c Y → Hom c W` and `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`), which is impossible.\n\nThe definition of `Hom_c_?` is flawed. It should be a functor `α → β → Type` or `α → Type → Type` depending on the convention. Let's assume the intended definition is `Hom_c : α → α → Type` where `Hom_c c Y = Hom Y c` (this is `Hom c Y` in the code, but this is not the standard `Hom`).\nOr, it could be `Hom_c : α → Type → Type` where `Hom_c c Y = Hom c Y`.\nLet's assume the latter. Then `map_comp` should be:\n`map_comp {Y Z W : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom Z W) : (fun h => comp h (comp f g)) = comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)`\nLet's check types:\n- `fun h => comp h (comp f g)` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c W`.\n- `fun h => comp h g` has type `Hom c Z → Hom c Y`.\n- `fun h => comp h f` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n- `comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)` is `λ h, (fun h' => comp h' g) ((fun h' => comp h' f) h)`.\n- This simplifies to `λ h, comp (comp h f) g`.\n- This has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n- This is not equal to `fun h => comp h (comp f g) : Hom c Y → Hom c W`.\n\nThere must be a mistake in the problem statement or the formalization. Let's assume the intended definition is `Hom_c : α → Type` where `Hom_c c = fun Y => Hom Y c`.\nThen, `map_comp` should be:\n`map_comp {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) : (fun h => comp h (comp f g)) = comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)`\nLet's check types:\n- `fun h => comp h (comp f g)` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n- `fun h => comp h g` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n- `fun h => comp h f` has type `Hom c Z → Hom c Y`.\n- `comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)` is `λ h, (fun h' => comp h' g) ((fun h' => comp h' f) h)`.\n- This simplifies to `λ h, comp (comp h f) g`.\n- This has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n- This is equal to `fun h => comp h (comp f g)` because `comp (comp h f) g = comp h (comp f g)` by associativity.\n\nThis suggests the definition should be:\n```tactics\ndef Hom_c_? {α : Type*} [Category α] (c : α) : Functor α Type where\n  F Y := Hom Y c\n  homF {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) := comp g f\n  map_id Y := by sorry\n  map_comp {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom Z W) := by\n    funext h\n    -- Goal: comp h (comp f g) = comp (comp h g) f\n    -- This is associativity of composition.\n    simp [comp]\n    <;> tauto\n```\nLet's recompute with this definition:\n- `F Y := Hom Y c`. This is `Type`.\n- `homF {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) := comp g f`. This has type `Hom Y Z → Hom c Y → Hom Y c`.\n  - `f : Hom Y Z` means `Y → Z`.\n  - `g : Hom c Y` means `c → Y`.\n  - `comp g f` means `g ∘ f : c → Z`. This is `Hom c Z`.\n  - So, `homF` should have type `∀ {Y Z : α}, Hom Y Z → Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n  - The provided definition `comp g f` is correct.\n- `map_id Y := by sorry`. This should be `homF (id Y) (id c) = id (Hom Y c)`. `comp (id c) (id Y) = id (Hom Y c)`. This is `id Y = id Y`. `rfl` should work.\n- `map_comp {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom Z W) := by ...`. This should prove `(fun h => comp h (comp f g)) = comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)`.\n  - `fun h => comp h (comp f g)` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c W`.\n  - `fun h => comp h g` has type `Hom c Z → Hom c Y`.\n  - `fun h => comp h f` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n  - `comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)` has type `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n  - The equality is between `Hom c Y → Hom c W` and `Hom c Y → Hom c Z`. This is impossible unless `W = Z`.\n\nThere must be a fundamental error in the problem statement or the formalization. Let's assume the intended definition is `Hom_c : α → Type` where `Hom_c c = fun Y => Hom c Y`.\nThen `map_comp` should be:\n`map_comp {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) : (fun h => comp h (comp f g)) = comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)`\nLet's recompute types with this definition:\n- `F Y := Hom c Y`. This is `Type`.\n- `homF {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) := comp g f`. This has type `Hom Y Z → Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n  - `f : Hom Y Z` means `Y → Z`.\n  - `g : Hom c Y` means `c → Y`.\n  - `comp g f` means `g ∘ f : c → Z`. This is `Hom c Z`.\n  - This is correct.\n- `map_id Y := by rfl`. `comp (id c) (id Y) = id (Hom c Y)`. This is `id Y = id Y`. `rfl` works.\n- `map_comp {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) : (fun h => comp h (comp f g)) = comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)`\n  - `fun h => comp h (comp f g)` takes `h : Hom c Y` and returns `comp h (comp f g) : Hom c Z`.\n  - `fun h => comp h g` takes `h : Hom c Z` and returns `comp h g : Hom c Y`.\n  - `fun h => comp h f` takes `h : Hom c Y` and returns `comp h f : Hom c Z`.\n  - `comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)` takes `h : Hom c Y` and returns `comp (fun h' => comp h' g) (fun h' => comp h' f) h`.\n    - This is `comp (comp h f) g`.\n    - So, the function is `λ h, comp (comp h f) g : Hom c Y → Hom c Z`.\n  - The equality is `fun h => comp h (comp f g) = fun h => comp (comp h f) g`.\n  - This is true by associativity of composition: `comp h (comp f g) = comp (comp h f) g`.\n  - The proof would be `funext h; simp [comp] <;> tauto`.\n\nThis suggests the definition `def Hom_c_? {α : Type*} [Category α] (c : α) : Functor α Type where F Y := Hom c Y ...` is incorrect.\nIt should be `def Hom_c_? {α : Type*} [Category α] (c : α) : α → Type where ...` or `def Hom_c_? {α : Type*} [Category α] (c : α) : α → α → Type where ...`.\nLet's assume the intended definition is `def Hom_c_? {α : Type*} [Category α] (c : α) : α → Type where F Y := Hom Y c`.\nThen `map_comp` should be:\n`map_comp {Y Z : α} (f : Hom Y Z) (g : Hom c Y) : (fun h => comp h (comp f g)) = comp (fun h => comp h g) (fun h => comp h f)`\n\nLet's construct this proof.\n\n```tactics\nimport CategoryTheoryInContextLean.Section_1_1\nimport CategoryTheoryInContextLean.Section_1_2\n\n/-!\n# Category Theory in Context - Section 1.3\n\nWe introduce functors, contravariant functors and the category of small categories.\nWe continue to use the custom definition of a category from Section 1.1.\n\n-/\n\nnamespace CategoryInContext\n\nopen Category\n\n-- definition 1.3.1\nclass Functor (α β : Type*) [C : Category α] [D : Category β] where\n  -- data\n  -- map on objects\n  F : α → β\n  -- map on morphisms\n  homF {X Y : α} : C.Hom X Y → D.Hom (F X) (F Y)\n  -- properties / laws\n  -- need to qualify id to avoid clash with id in root namespace.\n  map_id (X : α) : homF (id X) = Category.id (F X)\n  map_comp {X Y Z : α} (f : C.Hom X Y) (g : C.Hom Y Z) :\n    homF (f ≫ g) = homF f ≫ homF g\n\ndef EndoFunctor (α : Type*) [Category α] := @Functor α α\n\ndef IdFunctor {α : Type*} [Category α] : Functor α α where\n  F X := X\n  homF f := f\n  map_id _ := rfl\n  map_comp _ _ := rfl\n\n-- examples 1.3.2.i\ndef PowerSetFunctor : Functor Type Type where\n  F X := Set X\n  homF f := Set.image f\n  map_id X := by\n    simp [Category.id]\n    funext x\n    simp only [Set.image_id']\n  map_comp f g := by\n    simp [Category.comp]\n    funext x\n    simp only [Function.comp_apply]\n    exact Eq.symm (Set.image_image g f x)\n\n-- todo: add 1.3.2.ii-xi, once we have appropriate categories defined\n-- todo: add theorem 1.3.3\n\n-- definition 1.3.5\nclass ContraFunctor (α β :